node.text:
The WWW (Wood Wide Web).
cc: @brookeholm 

The Wood Wide Web—Earth’s original “Internet”—is a living, biological network happening right under our feet. 

Connected by miles of mycorrhizal fungi—which form tubes that weave themselves into roots—trees in some of the planet’s most ancient forests have the ability to communicate with one another through intricate chemical signaling. 

This network helps blueprint an epic story of alliances and betrayals within the forests of Earth. Through the WWW, trees are able to share nutrients, oxygen, and water between neighboring trees, warn each other about the threats of pathogenic attack, and even sabotage competing trees by spreading toxins through the soil to inhibit growth of certain species. 

An Internet hundreds of millions of years old, ceaselessly humming under the surface.
